`serializable()` is not a standard keyword or feature in C++. This term seems to be a placeholder or a hypothetical function used in the context of serialization and deserialization to indicate that a class or object can be serialized into a format that can be stored or transmitted and later deserialized back into its original form.

In the context of serialization in C++, the process of serializing an object involves converting its state into a format that can be easily stored in a file, exchanged over a network, or persisted in some other way. Serialization is often used in scenarios such as saving object state, transmitting data between systems, or storing complex data structures in a compact format.

Here's an example to illustrate a hypothetical usage of a `serializable()` function to indicate that a class is serializable:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <fstream>

class Serializable {
public:
    virtual void serialize(std::ostream& os) const = 0;
    virtual void deserialize(std::istream& is) = 0;
};

class Person : public Serializable {
private:
    int age;
    std::string name;

public:
    Person(int a, const std::string& n) : age(a), name(n) {}

    void serialize(std::ostream& os) const override {
        os << age << " " << name;
    }

    void deserialize(std::istream& is) override {
        is >> age >> name;
    }

    void displayInfo() const {
        std::cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << std::endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Person p(30, "Alice");

    std::ofstream outFile("person_data.txt");
    if (outFile.is_open()) {
        p.serialize(outFile);
        outFile.close();
    }

    Person newPerson(0, "");
    std::ifstream inFile("person_data.txt");
    if (inFile.is_open()) {
        newPerson.deserialize(inFile);
        inFile.close();
        newPerson.displayInfo();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

