Here is an example comparing the behavior with and without `std::move()` in C++. We will use a `Person` class to demonstrate moving an object to another object.

### Without `std::move()`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class Person {
public:
    std::string name;

    Person(const std::string& n) : name(n) {
        std::cout << "Constructing " << name << std::endl;
    }

    ~Person() {
        std::cout << "Destroying " << name << std::endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Creating a Person object
    Person p1("Alice");

    // Creating another Person object by copying p1
    Person p2 = p1;

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, when `Person p2 = p1;` is called, a copy of `p1` is made to create `p2`. This involves calling the copy constructor of the `Person` class to create a new object `p2`, resulting in a full copy of the `name` string.

### With `std::move()`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class Person {
public:
    std::string name;

    Person(const std::string& n) : name(n) {
        std::cout << "Constructing " << name << std::endl;
    }

    Person(Person&& other) noexcept : name(std::move(other.name)) {
        std::cout << "Moving " << other.name << " to " << name << std::endl;
    }

    ~Person() {
        std::cout << "Destroying " << name << std::endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Creating a Person object
    Person p1("Alice");

    // Creating another Person object by moving p1
    Person p2 = std::move(p1);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, when `Person p2 = std::move(p1);` is called, the move constructor of the `Person` class is invoked to create `p2` by efficiently transferring the resources (in this case, the `name` string) from `p1` to `p2`. The move constructor uses `std::move()` to indicate that the `name` resource can be efficiently transferred rather than copied.

Using `std::move()` in this context enables move semantics, which can be more efficient than making a full copy of the object, especially for resources like large strings, arrays, or memory allocations.

